      <hedline>
        <hl1>The Power Burden</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Oak Ridge National Laboratory research group leader Dr Theodore M Besmann letter on April 23 article holds New York's and New England's high-capacity nuclear plants must remain in full operation to balance national power grid</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''That Groan You Hear Is From the Power Grid'' (April 23), which discussed the strains on the nation's electrical network:</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''That Groan You Hear Is From the Power Grid'' (April 23), which discussed the strains on the nation's electrical network:</p>
        <p>A growing problem for the grid is everyone's desire to have power sources remote from their own region. Shutting power plants in the Northeast in favor of power from the Midwest increases pressure on the grid. We need to keep the high-capacity nuclear plants of New York and New England in full operation to balance the national grid.</p>
        <p>In addition, transmission losses can be substantial (up to 10 percent), which is a further incentive for maintaining regional power plants.</p>
        <p>In electricity as in politics, local power is very important.</p>
        <p>DR. THEODORE M. BESMANN  Oak Ridge, Tenn., April 23</p>
        <p>The writer is research group leader at the Oak Ridge National Laboratory.</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
